For the Municipal Accountant:
c. Effect the necessary adjustments on the erroneous recording of the advances to contractors account to correct the reported balances of affected PPE accounts.
Henceforth, observe proper recording and classification of accounts and transactions to avoid errors;

To Municipal Accountant:
a. Exert more effort to come up with a record that will settle the differences with the property custodian/GSO records;
b. Compute for the depreciation charges of the identified PPEs and make the necessary adjustment on the affected accounts;
For the Municipal Gen. Service Officer:
c. Conduct a complete inventory taking and submit the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) every January 31 of each year to the Office of the Auditor;
d. Expedite the disposal of the unserviceable properties to reflect the accurate and reliable amount of the PPE account;
e. Maintain complete and updated property cards and timely submit updated RPCPPE to the accounting office to facilitate reconciliation with the latter’s property ledger and make appropriate and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts to reflect the correct balance of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
f. Locate documents pertinent to the LGU properties preparatory to the conduct of the mandatory physical inventory.

To Municipal Accountant;
a. Observe the use of Perpetual Inventory Method pursuant to Section 114 of NGAS Manual in recording the Inventory account;
b. Record properly all purchases to its appropriate inventory account and maintain a supply ledger card for each type of inventory.
To Municipal Gen. Service Officer;
c. Maintain stock cards for supplies in your custody to account for the receipt and disposition of the same.
d. Prepare Monthly Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (MSSMI) duly supported by Requisition and Issuance Slip (RIS) from end-users for submission to the Accounting Office for proper recording of issuances of the inventories.

a. For the Municipal Assessor to prepare and update the Assessment Roll and provide the same to the Municipal Treasurer as basis for collection of real property and special education tax;
b. For the Municipal Treasurer to update the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR)/ Taxpayer’s index and furnish Accounting Office of the duly certified list of taxpayers, their amount due and collectible for the year. Henceforth, such list shall be provided at the final beginning of each year;
c. For the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the RPT receivable under SEF beginning balance to SET receivable and its corresponding deferred credit and record the beginning balance of the said receivables account and its related account based on the affected RPTAR/Tax Index Card report from the Office of the Municipal Treasurer.

a. A cash analysis should be made and the Local School Board should take into consideration the total available resources in the preparation of SEF annual budget. SEF unrestricted funds as identified at year end should be appropriated in the next year’s budget based on the guidelines in the utilization of SEF;
b. Observe timely preparation, review and approval of the SEF budget. Consider in the budget preparation the inclusion of programs, projects and activities in the Annual Investment Program to effectively prioritize education programs which are envisioned by the Municipality as well as complementing the same to the education budget of the national government;
c. Abide with the mandate of Section 100 of RA No. 7160 to conduct regular meeting or as often as may be necessary so that relevant issues may be discussed and changes in annual budget through supplemental budgets may be done.

a. Require the implementing offices or departments to re-visit the existing Memorandum of Agreement on trust funds in their possession and ensure that MOAs are still effective;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Heads of implementing departments, to implement proper liquidation of the amount granted as well as the refund of excess project funds to the source agency, if so provided in the terms of the grant;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to verify the existence of the funds in the bank, especially the excess or the long-outstanding balances, to facilitate the proper disposition of the funds.

For the Local Chief Executive and the Sangguniang Bayan:
a. Direct the preparation of a justification of the deficiencies noted herein and submit a joint explanation on why the subject payment of incentive should not be disallowed in audit;
b. Stop granting bonuses and incentives that are devoid of legal basis and refrain from approving disbursements that are tainted with irregularities;
For the Municipal Accountant:
c. Ensure that disbursements against public funds are supported with complete relevant documents before processing any disbursement.

For BAC to:
a. Require each department/office to prepare complete PPMP for all PPAs for their respective departments/offices as well as on its requirements;
b. Consolidate all Project Procurement Management Plans (PPMPs) into the APP prescribed format; For BAC and Accounting to:
c. Furnish the audit team a copy of perfected contract and each of all the documents forming part thereof by reference or incorporation for technical evaluation;
d. Ensure all government transactions are duly supported with complete documentary requirements under COA Circular 2012-001 and other existing issuances of COA.

1. The Local Chief Executive (LCE), as the Chairperson of the Municipal Development Council (MDC), to enjoin the MDC to revisit the project screening and prioritization criteria used in ranking and approving proposed projects for funding. If necessary, the MDC should develop and define, if not, improve the prioritization approach that is in accordance with applicable laws, rules and regulations, and adhere to these in the formulation of plans and budgets. New issuances such as the revised IRR of RA 9184, series of 2016 and DBM-DILG JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017, which provides updated guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the LDF should henceforth be considered;
2. The LCE should direct the Departments to provide substantive inputs in the formulation of plans and budgets;
3. The MDC should ensure that PPAs are properly linked with funding sources and service delivery outcomes;
4. The Local Finance Committee (LFC) should provide a comprehensive analysis of funding sources, as well as the MDC should provide a comprehensive list of proposed PPAs that the LGU may consider in developing its plans and budgets to ensure that funds will be allocated to its intended purpose, i.e. LDF for priority development projects;
5. The LCE should direct to stop the use of LDF to pay out expenses that are not related to and/or not connected with the implementation of development PPAs, such as research, planning and training expenses.

1. The management should implement the provisions of Sec. 305 (e) of RA 7160 and endeavor to have a balanced budget in each fiscal year of operation;
2. Ensure that Disbursement Vouchers and Obligation Requests are duly certified and approved by proper signatories. Also, ensure that all disbursements under special or trust funds are approved by the administrator of the fund;
3. Henceforth, the local finance committee shall adopt appropriate measures to control and monitor not only the appropriations and allotments but the cash availability as well. Ensure that 20% LDF, DRRMF, fund transfer from NGAs and other LGUs be utilized for the purpose for which the funds were intended;
4. For the Local Finance Committee to consider different strategies to increase the Municipality’s income and intensify collection and impose cost-cutting measures and prioritize projects and programs;
5. Henceforth, payment of penalty that may be imposed due to delayed remittance shall be paid/borne by the persons responsible.

1. Direct the MAO to maintain ledger cards and provide details of the PPE accounts to facilitate the reconciliation and recognition of depreciation expenses;
2. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all properties in accordance with existing regulations in order to establish actual existence;
3. Direct the GSO to maintain complete and updated property cards and timely submit updated RPCPPE to the accounting office to facilitate reconciliation with the latter’s property ledger and make appropriate and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts to reflect the correct balance of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
4. Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to locate documents pertinent to the LGU properties preparatory to the conduct of the mandatory physical inventory;
5. Create an inventory team to conduct a complete physical count / inventory of all properties in accordance with existing regulations and in order to establish the actual existence;
6. Make appropriate and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts.
7. Direct the MAO to transfer the CIP record of completed projects to its appropriate asset accounts and the related depreciation expense thereat should also be computed and properly recorded. Further, locate pertinent data and documents to identify the projects covered by the CIP for infrastructure assets to facilitate proper classification of accounts if the projects were already completed.

1. Prepare LDRRMF Investment Plan for all the prior years’ unexpended balances as well as supplemental budgets. Regularly review and update such plans to consider current vulnerabilities and timely implement those approved pre-disaster PPAs;
2. Adhere to the provision of COA Circular 2012-002 by transferring the prior years’ unexpended balances to Trust Liability – DRRM account and maintaining subsidiary account on a by year and by source basis;
3. Also, include disclosure notes of the amount and details of the unexpended balance of DRRM Fund in the Notes to Financial Statement;
4. Maximize available resources through timely implementation of PPAs and utilization of prior years’ unexpended balances prioritizing those nearing reversion to the unappropriated surplus of General Fund;
5. Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2012-001 relative to the documentary requirements for each type of disbursement;
6. Conduct a physical inventory count of all the supplies and PPEs and prepare an inventory list following the prescribed format in COA Circular 2014-002. Reconcile the inventory records as reflected in the books with the actual physical count. Develop standard policy on the timely submission of Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) and Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) of those already issued relief goods and supplies.

1. Ensure that cash advances shall only be given for a legally authorized specific purpose and adequately supported with relevant supporting documents;
2. Adhere with the provisions cited in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, hence, stop granting cash advance to Elected Officials except only for their official traveling expenses;
3. Request the designated Municipal Accountant to send the FINAL demand letter for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of the overdue unliquidated cash advances by the concerned officials and employees;
4. Stop granting additional cash advances to officials and employees until the previous ones have been liquidated and/or settled;
5. Prepare the financial statements in accordance with the PPSAS, hence, advances granted to officers and employees should be initially recorded under Advances to Officers and Employees (Account No. 1-03-05-040);
6. Prepare adjusting entry to reclassify erroneous entry made under Advances to Officers and Employees and Due to LGUs Accounts amounting to P891,840.00; and
7. Adhere with the provisions cited in COA Cir. No. 92-382 and submit to the audit team the liquidation vouchers/reports as well as its supporting documents currently in the accounting custody, otherwise reconstruct the balance of outstanding advances to officers and employees and reinstate previously recorded liquidation not duly supported by necessary documents.
8. Withhold the salary of officials and employees who fail or refuse to liquidate and/or settle their cash advances after giving due notice and final demand.

1. Ensure that the budgetary allocations and actual expenditures for Personal Services are within the 45% limitation to avoid future disallowances of transactions;
2. Henceforth, lump sum are avoided, instead, ensure that the local budget operationalizes the approved local development plans and contains identified objects of expenditures for each function, activity, and project. For the ensuing year, the LGU, thru the Municipal Planning and Development Officer, shall adhere to the review notes of the Municipal Budget Office, taking into consideration the conditions, if any, anent to the declaration of budget as operative.
3. The Municipal Budget Officer will ensure that the guidelines and procedures in augmentation are strictly followed.

1. Request the MAO to make necessary correcting entries to properly classify the inter-agency and intra-agency accounts;
2. Stop utilizing the PDAF and exert extra effort in tracing the source of fund. Require the Municipal Accountant to settle the balances by remitting it to the National Treasury in compliance to the Supreme Court Decision;
3. Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2012-001 relative to the documentary requirements for each type of disbursement.

1. The designate Municipal Accountant should seek assistance of the depository banks to recapture necessary information relative to the unrecorded, misclassified and closed depository accounts. Analyze accounts, establish discrepancies and prepare necessary journal entries to reflect the correct cash balances of these accounts;
2. Also, the Local Finance Committee coordinate with the Sanggunian Secretary in locating copy of documents such as Sanggunian Resolution authorizing the opening and closing (if any) of LGU’s depository accounts;
3. Adhere with provision of COA Cir. No. 92-382 dated July 3, 1992 in the opening, maintaining and closing of depository accounts;
4. The management should consider hiring competent personnel to address the limited manpower in the accounting department;
5. The designate Municipal Accountant should implement the provisions of COA Circular No. 96-011 and record adjustments for valid reconciling items as reflected in the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) prepared by the Accounting Office;
6. Henceforth, the BRS submitted to the COA Auditor should be supported by copies of the bank statements, JEV recording reconciling items that require correction in the books of accounts, as well as a copy of the letter to the respective bank informing them of errors noted in the BRS (other than those resulting from the timing of recording of transactions);
7. The designate Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer, with the aid of BRS, reconcile their records. Establish the discrepancies and effect the necessary adjustments both in the general ledger and cashbooks;
8. Monitor regularly the cash balances and transactions to determine proper use of the accounts. Close depository accounts in which the purpose had already been satisfied to avoid possible dormancy charges or below maintaining balance bank charges;
9. Prepare adjusting entries to recognize interest income and to reclassify balances from fund transfers booked under Due from Other Fund to Cash-in-Bank Account. Henceforth, ensure that all transaction is properly recorded in accordance with Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards (PPSAS).

1. Request the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Heads of implementing units, to implement proper liquidation of the amount granted as well as the refund of excess project funds to the Source Agency or transfer to its General Fund, if allowed in the terms of grant;
2. Closely coordinate with the Source Agency to expedite the release of price amendment and if possible, update the Sources Agency of the prevailing market prices to avoid unnecessary delays in the implementation of PPAs;
3. Execute without delay the intended PPAs of the fund transfers so that the benefits derived therefrom may already be enjoyed by the intended beneficiaries;
4. Request the MAO to coordinate with the Source Agencies and facilitate reconciliation of inter-agency transfers and ensure that all funds downloaded to the LGU are properly recognized and recorded in the books of accounts in the proper accounting period.

We recommend the following:
Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to locate documents pertinent to the LGU properties preparatory to the conduct of the mandatory physical inventory;
Create an inventory team to conduct a complete physical count/inventory of all properties in accordance with existing regulations and in order to establish the actual existence;
Submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plants and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with the latter’s ledger cards and furnish the same Report to the Office of the Auditor;
Maintain and update property records for periodical reconciliation with the Accounting records; and
Make appropriate and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the local chief executive direct the concerned officials to-
create an inventory team at an earliest possible time to conduct a complete physical inventory (by fund) of all properties owned by the Municipality and prepare complete reports thereon in order to established the actual existence and ensure the accuracy of the reported PPE balances at an aggregate amount of P134.881M;
submit a copy of the reports of said actual physical count of PPE to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with its ledger cards, and to the Auditor’s Office;
maintain and update property records and reconcile periodically the PPE ledger cards of the accounting unit and the property cards if the GSO; and 
effect the necessary adjustments of records on the basis of the results of the reconciliation of PPE accounts in the financial statements.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide ledger cards / details on each and every account on the Property, Plant and Equipment, such as the acquisition cost, dates, number of depreciable years and the corresponding accumulated depreciation;
Require the General Services Officer to maintain complete and updated property cards to facilitate periodic reconciliation with the Accounting unit
Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to locate documents pertinent to the LGU properties preparatory to the conduct of the mandatory physical inventory;
Create an inventory team to conduct a complete physical count / inventory of all properties in accordance with existing regulations and in order to establish the actual existence;
Submit updated Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with the latter's ledger cards and furnish the same Report to the Office of the Auditor; and
